(11, 'Energy needs throughout pregnancy', 'The main recommendation is to eat a healthy, balanced diet as described in the Malaysian Dietary Guidelines 2020 (NCCFN, 2021). The guidelines suggest that the proportion of macronutrients from total energy intake should be 50-65% carbohydrates, 10-20% protein, and 25-35% fat. The Recommended Nutrient Intakes for Malaysia (NCCFN, 2017) and the usual intake of the population help guide the number of servings for daily meals to achieve at least 90% of the RNI for energy, carbohydrates, protein, and fat. The energy requirement throughout pregnancy depends on factors like maternal pre-pregnancy weight status, physical activity, and the physiological demands of each trimester. The energy intake must meet the demands of maternal metabolism, physical activity, fetal growth, and the growth of other tissues such as fat mass, breast tissue, uterus, and placenta. The goal is to achieve appropriate weight gain to minimize the risks of adverse maternal and fetal outcomes.\r\n\r\n### 1.2 Metabolism during Pregnancy\r\n\r\nExtra energy is needed during pregnancy to support the growth and maintenance of the fetus, placenta, and maternal tissues (Jasper et al., 2019; Tran et al., 2019). The increase in energy needs is due to the increased metabolism of active tissues, such as the maternal cardiovascular, renal, and respiratory systems, as well as tissue synthesis. The average increase in metabolic rate throughout pregnancy is 4.5% for the first trimester, 10.8% for the second trimester, and 24.0% in the third trimester (Butte & King, 2005). This increased energy requirement also helps store energy for postpartum and breastfeeding.\r\n\r\nOptimal maternal and fetal outcomes depend on sufficient nutrient intake to meet both maternal and fetal needs. Energy is the primary nutrient that determines gestational weight gain and supports the pregnancy process. The extra energy required supports the growth and maintenance of the fetus, placenta, and maternal tissues, as well as the increased metabolism of active tissues. The energy consumption during pregnancy is linked to increased metabolism and physical activity, estimated at 77,000 kcal (FAO/WHO/UNU, 2004). The pregnancy process increases metabolic levels by about 10.7 ± 5.4 kcal per week, while the energy used increases by 5.2 ± 12.8 kcal per week (Most et al., 2019). The total increase in metabolism can be estimated according to the pregnant woman\'s resting energy expenditure (REE) (FAO/WHO/UNU, 2004). Studies of well-nourished women who gained adequate body mass during pregnancy estimate a cumulative increase of 147.8 MJ (35,330 kcal) for a 12 kg weight gain (EFSA Panel, 2013). The increased energy requirement during pregnancy is necessary to store energy for postpartum and breastfeeding.\r\n\r\nreferences: National Coordinating Committee on Food and Nutrition (NCCFN) Ministry of Health Malaysia 2023 \r\n', '11-ContentLinkHeader.jpg', 2, 1, '2024-07-30 10:12:07'),
(12, 'Benefits of meeting the energy and  macronutrients needs ', 'Meeting energy needs during pregnancy can lead to desirable gestational weight gain (GWG) and optimal pregnancy outcomes (Most et al., 2019). However, a systematic review and meta-analysis of observational studies found no significant relationship between the increase in energy intake from early to late pregnancy and GWG (Jebeile et al., 2016). Underreporting of food intake might explain these findings, highlighting the need for high-quality longitudinal studies.\r\n\r\nEven though there is no direct link between energy intake and GWG, consuming nutrient-dense food to meet energy requirements is essential. This helps women meet the necessary micronutrient intake. Without increasing energy intake, women may not get enough essential nutrients, which can negatively affect pregnancy outcomes. Extra energy is also necessary to support fetal growth, the growth of maternal tissues, and changes in maternal energy metabolism.\r\n\r\nA recent study in Japan involving 89,817 mother-child pairs examined how energy intake during pregnancy and GWG influenced birth weight (Minami et al., 2022). The study found a positive association between energy intake during pregnancy and birth weight, mediated by GWG. Excessive energy intake, whether too low or too high, increased the risk of abnormal birth size, emphasizing the importance of meeting optimal energy needs for appropriate GWG and fetal growth.\r\n\r\nMeeting energy and macronutrient needs during breastfeeding is also crucial for the health and well-being of both mothers and infants. Proper nutrition supports breast milk production, promotes optimal growth and development for the infant, and helps maintain the mother\'s nutritional status. A recent meta-regression analysis found a positive association between maternal BMI and human milk fat in term-born infants aged 1 to 6 months (Daniel et al., 2021). Specifically, for every 1 kg/m² increase in maternal BMI, there was a corresponding 0.56 g/L increase in milk-fat concentration. However, no association was observed between maternal BMI and human milk energy or total protein levels (Daniel et al., 2021). Additionally, a study among 367 pregnant women in Minneapolis and Oklahoma found that higher maternal diet quality at one and three months postpartum was associated with lower infant adiposity (Tahir et al., 2019). These findings underscore the importance of maternal nutrition and diet quality during breastfeeding in influencing both the composition of breast milk and the long-term health outcomes of infants.\r\n\r\nreferences: National Coordinating Committee on Food and Nutrition (NCCFN) Ministry of Health Malaysia 2023', '12-ContentLinkHeader.webp', 2, 1, '2024-07-30 10:16:48'),
(13, 'Special Considerations ', 'a. Maternal Obesity and Underweight\r\nThe ideal condition is to have an optimal BMI and good nutritional status before pregnancy. However, an increasing number of women are entering pregnancy with a weight exceeding the healthy range. This is critical as obesity during pregnancy significantly contributes to maternal and perinatal morbidity, with a rising global prevalence among reproductive-aged women (Giouleka et al., 2023). Women with obesity are more likely to experience complications such as excessive GWG (over 60% prevalence), gestational diabetes mellitus (GDM), hypertensive disorders, non-elective cesarean sections, and having macrosomic infants (Kim & Ayabe, 2023). However, weight loss through restrictive diets is not recommended during pregnancy as it can lead to inadequate nutrient intake, negatively impacting fetal growth and development.\r\n\r\nThe Institute of Medicine (IOM) recommendations for energy intake were mainly based on studies involving pregnant women without obesity (IOM, 2009). Women with overweight and obesity are twice as likely to exceed these guidelines, leading to only one-third of pregnant women achieving the recommended weight gain for healthy maternal, neonatal, and infant outcomes. Therefore, recommending appropriate energy and macronutrient needs is crucial for women with obesity during pregnancy. Most et al. (2019b) recommended that the daily energy intake during the second and third trimesters should not exceed energy expenditure to achieve the recommended rate of weight gain. This means that pregnant women with obesity should not consume additional energy intake, as the extra energy for fetal development can be compensated by maternal fat mass without adverse effects on maternal and fetal outcomes (Most et al., 2019a). Therefore, the energy needs for women with obesity must be personalized and include physical activity and improved dietary quality. Excessive energy intake rather than decreased energy expenditure after pregnancy can lead to postpartum weight gain (Most et al., 2020). Thus, women should be advised not to overeat after pregnancy, and appropriate dietary recommendations should be given to women with obesity during the postpartum period.\r\n\r\nSimilarly, women with an underweight pre-pregnancy BMI have a significantly higher risk of delivering a low birth weight (LBW) infant. A cross-sectional survey in Taiwan found that processed food consumption in the third trimester was associated with LBW. Nutritious food during pregnancy is critical in preventing LBW, especially among older and pre-pregnant underweight women. Thus, prenatal nutrition advice should emphasize individualized optimal nutrition (Chen, Loy & Chen, 2023). LBW babies are more likely to not survive during the first month of life and tend to suffer from long-term consequences such as a higher risk of stunting, low IQ, and a higher risk of adult-onset non-communicable diseases (NCDs) like obesity and type 2 diabetes (UNICEF, 2023).\r\n\r\nb. Multiple Pregnancy\r\nThe maternal metabolic rate in twin pregnancies is approximately 10% greater than in singleton pregnancies. Multiple gestations demand more physiologically than singleton pregnancies, including increased plasma volume and decreased levels of hemoglobin, albumin, and water-soluble vitamins. Generally, the energy demand is higher for multiple pregnancies. However, more position statements from scientific societies are needed to specify the required energy intake. Due to a lack of studies on the actual energy needs of women pregnant with twins, Wierzejska (2022) theoretically assumed that an additional 150 kcal/day might be needed compared to singleton pregnancies, aiming for a target GWG of 20 kg. It is also estimated that a 40% higher-calorie diet may maintain a woman\'s nutritional state during a twin pregnancy. There is a lack of evidence for the nutritional management of other multiple pregnancies (triplets, quadruplets), but they can be managed similarly to twin gestations (Kominiarek & Rajan, 2016).\r\n\r\nc. Adolescent Pregnancy\r\nPregnancy physiology differs in teenagers compared to adult women. Pregnant teenagers, especially those under 16, face a significant risk of stillbirth, preterm delivery, low birth weight, and neonatal mortality due to the continuing and incomplete growth of the teenagers themselves (Wallace, 2019). Nutritional needs change during pregnancy, with increased requirements for energy and several micronutrients. Optimal dietary intake is critically important during continued growth and development. However, the dietary patterns of pregnant teens are generally less healthy than those of adult pregnant women. Teen diets often include higher intakes of snacks and processed foods, fewer fruits and vegetables, and fewer nutritional supplements (Marvin-Dowle et al., 2018; Samano et al., 2022).\r\n\r\nSystematic reviews report that energy and micronutrient intakes in adolescent pregnancies are below recommended levels. Blood markers indicate that anemia and low iron status may be prevalent in this population (Marvin-Dowle, Burley & Soltani, 2016). Teen pregnancy is also a risk factor for both excessive (37%) and insufficient (41%) GWG (Samano et al., 2022). The diet of Mexican pregnant teens associated with excessive GWG includes cereals, grains, and animal-sourced foods but inadequate legumes. However, energy and macronutrient intake and eating habits were not directly associated with GWG (Samano et al., 2022). Therefore, the recommended energy intake for pregnant teens must align with their age-specific needs, considering the pregnancy trimesters.\r\n\r\nd. Vegetarians\r\nThe American Dietetic Association states that vegan diets are healthful, nutritionally adequate, and safe for all age groups and physiological conditions, including childhood, adolescence, pregnancy, and breastfeeding (Vesanto, Craig & Levin, 2016). The Physicians Committee for Responsible Medicine also supports a plant-based diet as a healthy choice at every life stage, including pregnancy and breastfeeding (Hanson et al., 2015).\r\n\r\nHowever, it is crucial to include all food groups in the daily diet, considering their nutritional values. Both insufficient and excessive intake should be avoided as they can significantly impact health. Balanced vegetarian diets meet the nutritional needs of all life cycle stages, including pregnancy and breastfeeding. Well-planned vegetarians tend to consume less overall energy, lower dietary fat (particularly saturated fat) and dietary cholesterol, and higher intakes of fruits, vegetables, whole grains, nuts, soy products, fiber, and phytochemicals than non-vegetarians. Due to the variability in vegetarian diets, individuals need to be familiar with their nutritional needs and potential dietary deficiencies.\r\n\r\nThe proportions of macronutrients required during breastfeeding do not differ from those of non-lactating women. Lactating women can acquire all essential amino acids from high-quality protein sources such as meat, fish, eggs, and milk. For vegetarian women, plant protein sources, including legumes, nuts, fruits, starchy root vegetables, and cereals, should be combined to ensure all essential amino acids are consumed. Minimally processed carbohydrates and fiber should be consumed in similar proportions as in the pregnancy diet (Hanson et al., 2015). Pregnant and breastfeeding women on a vegan diet should pay special attention to their dietary intake and seek advice from healthcare professionals.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nreference: National Coordinating Committee on Food and Nutrition (NCCFN) Ministry of Health Malaysia 2023\r\n\r\n\r\n', '13-ContentLinkHeader.jpg', 2, 1, '2024-07-30 10:26:56');

