(18, 'Pretexting attack examples', 'image291.png', 2, '<b>Internet service provider</b><br><br>\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image30.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\nIn this scenario, a person posing as an internet service provider shows up on your doorstep for a routine check. Once they get inside, they have free rein to tap into your devices and snoop through your valuable information.<br><br>\r\nTIP: Don’t let a service provider inside your home without an appointment. If you’re wary, pry into their position and their knowledge of your service plan to unveil any holes in their story. As for a service company ID, and consider scheduling a later appointment be contacting the company.<br><br>\r\n<b>Subject line requests</b><br><br>\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image80.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n“Are you available?” “Can you help me?” “Nice to see you!” All of these can be pretty catchy email subject lines or, rather, convincing subject lines. In this pretexting example, an urgent or mysterious subject line is meant to get you to open a message and fulfill an information request from a cybercriminal posing as a trusted source, be it a boss, acquaintance, or colleague.<br><br>\r\nTIP: If the message seems urgent or out of the blue, verify it with the sender on a different communication channel to confirm it’s legitimate.<br><br>\r\nReferences:<a href=\"https://us.norton.com/blog/online-scams/what-is-pretexting\">https://us.norton.com/blog/online-scams/what-is-pretexting</a><br><br>\r\n<b><u>Real-life example in Malaysia</u></b><br><br>\r\n<b>LHDN Scam:</b><br><br>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>\r\n    TAX ARREARS / TAX EVASION SCHEME\r\n    <p>Victims receive messages, phone calls, letters, or emails from a syndicate informing them of outstanding taxes that have not been settled. The victims are required to settle the tax arrears by transferring money to a non-LHDNM (Inland Revenue Board of Malaysia) bank account.</p>\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    TAX EVASION, CRIMINAL ACTIVITY, AND MONEY LAUNDERING\r\n    <p>Victims are contacted alleging their involvement in tax evasion, criminal activity, and money laundering. As a result, the victim&#39;s bank account will be blocked under the Anti-Money Laundering, Pencegahan Pembiayaan Keganasan dan Hasil Daripada Aktiviti Haram 2001 (AMLATFPUAA). The victims will then be connected to speak with \"police officers\" or \"officers of the Malaysian Anti-Corruption Commission (SPRM)\" or authorities responsible for the victim&#39;s case with the aim of creating panic among the victims. To prevent freezing of all funds in the victim&#39;s account, the victims are directed to transfer the money to a third-party bank account, which will supposedly be transferred back to the victim&#39;s account once the victim&#39;s \"criminal case\" is resolved.</p>\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    TAX COLLECTION VISIT / AUDIT / TAX INVESTIGATION\r\n    <p>Victims receive visits from \"LHDNM officers\" purportedly to collect taxes or conduct tax audits and investigations. The syndicate will request the victims&#39; income or business documents and inform them that they have misreported their income taxes. Victims are directed to make payment of the estimated \"additional tax balance\" into a non-LHDNM account.</p>\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    PROFIT FROM STOCK SALES\r\n    <p>Victims receive letters or emails informing them that they are involved in stock trading activities with an investment company and are required to make tax arrears payments based on instructions provided by the fraud syndicate.</p>\r\n		<center><img class=\"img-content\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image23.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br>\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    OVERPAID TAX REFUND\r\n    <p>Victims receive an email informing them that they have overpaid taxes that will be refunded by LHDNM. Victims are asked to click on the link provided in the fake email, and instructions will be given to disclose their bank account details, including internet banking passwords, purportedly to facilitate the processing of the excess tax refund by LHDNM.</p>\r\n		<center><img class=\"img-content\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image391.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br>\r\n  </li>\r\n</ol><br><br>\r\nIf you ever receive any kind of messages, emails, or calls, please follow these steps:<br><br>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>Verify with LHDNM (Inland Revenue Board of Malaysia):\r\n    <ul>\r\n      <li>Call the Hasil Care Line at 03-8911 1000 / 603-89111100 (for overseas calls).</li>\r\n      <li>Use the HASiL Live Chat feature.</li>\r\n      <li>Fill out the Feedback Form on the LHDNM official website at <a href=\"https://maklumbalaspelanggan.hasil.gov.my/MaklumBalas/ms-my/\" target=\"_blank\">https://maklumbalaspelanggan.hasil.gov.my/MaklumBalas/ms-my/</a>.</li>\r\n      <li>Visit a nearby LHDNM branch.</li>\r\n    </ul>\r\n  </li>\r\n	<li>Ensure that tax arrears payments are made only to LHDNM.</li>\r\n  <li>Avoid returning calls to unfamiliar phone numbers. Verify LHDNM phone numbers on the official LHDNM portal.</li>\r\n  <li>Check the Tax Collection Framework, Tax Audit Framework, and Tax Investigation Framework on the official LHDNM portal at www.hasil.gov.my > Perundangan (Legislation) to confirm the legitimate procedures for tax collection, audit, and investigation activities by LHDNM.</li>\r\n  <li>Verify that official LHDNM emails use the domain @hasil.gov.my.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<br><br><center><img class=\"img-content\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image46.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n\r\nReference:<a href=\"https://www.hasil.gov.my/peringatan-penipuan/\">https://www.hasil.gov.my/peringatan-penipuan/</a><br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>Kastam Scam: </b><br><br><center>\r\n<img class=\"img-content\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image261.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n<br><br><center><img class=\"img-content\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image13.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n<br><br><center><img class=\"img-content\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image6.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\nReference:<a href=\"https://www.mkn.gov.my/web/ms/2022/09/20/waspada-ancaman-scam-melibatkan-jabatan-kastam-diraja-malaysia/\">https://www.mkn.gov.my/web/ms/2022/09/20/waspada-ancaman-scam-melibatkan-jabatan-kastam-diraja-malaysia/</a><br><br>\r\n<b>Parcel Scam:</b><br><br>\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content30\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image27.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\nIf you’ve received any of the above emails<br><br>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>DO NOT click on any of the links.</li>\r\n<li>Delete it and do not forward it to limit circulation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 9),
(19, 'What is baiting?', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/_0IQInSl5iI', 1, 'Baiting is a type of attack that utilizes physical media and preys on the victim&#39;s curiosity or greed, resembling a real-world version of the \"Trojan Horse\" tactic. It shares similarities with phishing attacks, but what sets it apart from other forms of social engineering is the lure of a promised item or reward that hackers exploit to entice victims. Baiters may tempt users with offers of free vouchers such as foodpanda in exchange for their login credentials on a specific website or free money in exchange they need to do provided tasks. <br><br>\r\nOne of the notorious baiting scams in Malaysia involves offering individuals \"part-time\" jobs with the promise of rewarding commissions upon completing tasks. Recently, a man was scammed out of RM16,000 after being enticed by the prospect of substantial commissions. The victim, similarly to other cases, was instructed to purchase products on the Shopee shopping app and was promised a 10% profit from these purchases. He followed the instructions, added the items to her cart, and provided screenshots to the designated admin. Furthermore, he was directed to transfer the total amount for the purchased items to a specified account number.\r\n<br><br><center><img class=\"img-content30\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image301.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n\r\nInitially, the victim received his initial capital and the promised commission of RM41.50 for the first and second tasks. However, when he completed six transactions, the system suddenly went down, causing suspicion.<br><br>\r\nFor the third task, he was required to make six additional transactions to the provided account number, despite it taking longer than expected.<br><br>\r\nWhen the victim requested a refund of his money, he was informed that he had to pay a penalty of RM3,299. After making the payment, the admin claimed that the system was down again, and the victim was told to wait until the following day for a refund. It was at this point that he realised he had fallen victim to a scam and promptly filed a police report.<br><br>\r\nReference:<a href=\"https://lobakmerah.com/hati-hati-scammer-part-time-job-lelaki-dedah-kena-scam-rm16k-lepas-ditawar-komisen-lumayan/\" target=\"_blank\">https://lobakmerah.com/hati-hati-scammer-part-time-job-lelaki-dedah-kena-scam-rm16k-lepas-ditawar-komisen-lumayan/</a><br><br>\r\n\r\n', 10),
(20, 'Baiting attack techniques', 'image2.png', 2, 'Baiting is a type of social engineering attack that exploits human psychology to deceive individuals and retrieve confidential information for the attackers&#39; benefit, often to gain financial advantages. By leveraging enticing offers and taking advantage of human curiosity, fear, and greed, cybercriminals use baiting techniques to manipulate their targets into revealing sensitive data or performing actions that compromise their security. The ultimate objective of baiting attacks is to deceive individuals into providing personal information or financial resources that can be exploited by the attackers.<br><br>\r\nEvery human being has some level of curiosity, fear, and greed influencing his decisions and behavior and that is what criminals who set up baiting attacks exploit. Cybercriminals can achieve this through different techniques.<br><br>\r\nBelow are the common baiting attack methods to be aware of. <br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>Tempting Offers</b><br><br>\r\nCybercriminals find major success using tempting offers to lure victims. They send targets enticing offers via ads, social media, email, or free downloadable content. They offer their victims access to free music, movies, games, and software. These offers are usually difficult to resist. <br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>Malware-Infected Devices</b><br><br>\r\nAnother way cybercriminals execute a baiting attack is through malware-infected USB devices or flash drives. They leave the device in the open such as the company lobby, reception office, in front of the house or even in the mailbox. Once an employee or individual inserts the flash into their system, it automatically installs malware on the computer and infects the organization’s network.\r\n', 11),
(21, 'How to spot baiting?', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/R12_y2BhKbE', 1, 'Healthy skepticism and mindfulness can forestall baiting attacks. Here are some tips to spot it:<br>\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>Research and verify: Before engaging with any opportunity or offer, thoroughly research the company, organization, or individual involved. Look for official websites, reviews, and independent sources to verify their legitimacy. Be skeptical of unsolicited emails, messages, or phone calls. Learn to think skeptically about any offer that’s too good to be true.</li>\r\n  <li>Be cautious of unrealistic promises: Scammers often entice victims with promises of high pay, easy work, or extravagant rewards. If an offer seems too good to be true, it probably is. Exercise caution and use your judgment to identify potential red flags.</li>\r\n  <li>Protect your personal information: Never share sensitive personal information, such as your Social Security number, bank account details, or credit card information, unless you have verified the legitimacy of the recipient and have a legitimate reason to provide it.</li>\r\n  <li>Use secure and reputable platforms: When searching for part-time jobs or engaging in online transactions, use reputable websites or platforms that have established credibility. Look for secure browsing indicators like HTTPS in the website URL.</li>\r\n  <li>Beware of upfront payments or fees: Scammers may ask you to pay upfront fees or provide financial information before starting a job or claiming a reward. Legitimate employers or companies generally do not require payment from employees or winners.</li>\r\n  <li>Trust your instincts: If something feels off or suspicious, trust your gut instinct. If you&#39;re unsure about a job offer, request more information or consult with friends, family, or professionals who can offer objective advice.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 11),
(22, 'How to avoid baiting?', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/eII2Gx3iG10', 1, 'Human curiosity and greed are inevitable — we all like enticing offers and gifts. However, we should be careful to avoid becoming a victim of baiting. Organizations should implement different measures to help counter such attacks.  A successful attack can cause financial losses and reputational damages. Here are a few tips to avoid baiting in cybersecurity: <br><br>\r\n<b>Stay Alert</b><br><br>\r\nBe prudent of communications that force you to act instantly. Attackers try to instill a sense of urgency to manipulate your emotions. So slow down and think before you react or perform any action. A good example is an offer that would expire in minutes. <br><br>\r\n\r\nCybercriminals can share links in emails, tweets, posts, and messages to compromise systems or lure their victims into revealing sensitive information. If it looks suspicious, you probably shouldn’t engage it.<br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>Don’t Follow Links Blindly</b><br><br>\r\nWhen you receive a message that includes a link, double-check it before engaging it. Do you know where it’s coming from? If you don’t know where the link will direct you to, don’t click on it. <br><br>\r\n\r\nThe best practice is to hover on the link with your mouse to see where it might send you. If you doubt its legitimacy. \r\n', 12),
(23, 'What is the impact on baiting victims?', 'image61.png', 2, '<ol>\r\n  <li>Financial Loss: Social engineering baiting often aims to deceive individuals into providing financial information, such as credit card details or bank account credentials. Falling victim to such scams can result in financial loss, identity theft, or unauthorized access to personal accounts.</li>\r\n  <li>Privacy Breach: By tricking individuals into revealing personal information or login credentials, social engineering baiting can lead to a significant breach of privacy. This can result in compromised online accounts, exposure of sensitive data, or even potential blackmail.</li>\r\n  <li>Reputational Damage: Some social engineering baiting techniques involve manipulating individuals into sharing confidential or embarrassing information. The subsequent disclosure of such information can lead to reputational damage, both personally and professionally. This can impact relationships, job prospects, or even result in public humiliation.</li>\r\n  <li>Emotional and Psychological Impact: Falling victim to social engineering baiting can have a profound emotional and psychological impact. Individuals may experience feelings of shame, guilt, or betrayal. The breach of trust can also cause anxiety, stress, or a sense of vulnerability, impacting overall well-being.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', 12),
(24, 'Common method of baiting', 'image121.png', 2, '<b>Employ Online Baiting</b><br><br>\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content30\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image60.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content30\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image421.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\nIt could be a regular day, you’re checking your email when you come across a message stating that you could be a winner of a drawing or your relative passed away and left you some money. Anything with this kind of messaging should draw red flags, especially if you don’t remember entering the contest.<br><br>\r\nThe reason for this is if you play along, they’ll ask you to provide more personal information. This can include your password, cvv and bank account number to receive the winnings.<br><br>\r\nIn most instances, this is nothing more than a phishing scam. Logically, most reputable companies won’t ask for your cvv number nor your bank account information through an email. They’ll either send you paperwork or call to verify they have the right person before they even begin disbursing money.<br><br>\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content30\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image231.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content30\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image431.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n<b>We Need Your Help Messages</b><br><br>\r\nAnother common scheme involves a problem they need your assistance with. One way hackers mask this is by pretending to be your bank. The email will say something along the lines of “your account has had uncommon activity” then they provide a link for you to click on to fix it.<br><br>\r\nOf course, the link will send you to a landing page that might resemble your bank’s website. From there, you’ll follow prompts to enter your personal information and the hackers will use or sell that information to the highest bidder.<br><br>\r\nIt’s important to keep in mind that banks have other ways of alerting you to uncommon account activity. Often, this takes the form of a phone call from the fraud department or a text message. However, text messages can be trickier since hackers can remote access phones, so the best course of action, if you receive a text, is to contact your bank through the phone number on the back of your debit or credit card.<br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>An Offer You Cannot Refuse</b><br><br>\r\n\r\nMany of us shop for deals, and because of this we become bombarded with emails about all the latest trends. Hackers picked up on this and have devised ways of mirroring their message to coincide with emails you would receive from online auction sites and classifieds.<br><br>\r\nIn addition, the message will include some eye-popping deal (think a newer computer for RM500 to appeal to your budget sensibilities. That said, if a deal is too good to be true, chances are it is. It’s important to first research the seller’s reputation and if you cannot find one, Google the ad to see if it’s appeared other places on the web. If this is a scammer trying to make a quick buck, there’s a good chance you might find one.<br><br>\r\nUltimately, hackers use a variety of online baiting tools to try to prompt you to action. If you have had files stolen due to malware from these types of social engineering schemes, know help is only a phone call away.<br><br>\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content30\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image221.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content30\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image491.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n\r\n<b>Investment Scam</b><br><br>\r\n\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content30\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image182.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content30\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image52.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n<b>Job Scam</b><br><br>\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content30\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image171.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content30\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image371.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n\r\nReference:<a href=\"https://www.mkn.gov.my/web/ms/2022/08/15/jangan-terpedaya-penipuan-tawaran-kerja-di-platform-e-dagang/\" target=\"_blank\">https://www.mkn.gov.my/web/ms/2022/08/15/jangan-terpedaya-penipuan-tawaran-kerja-di-platform-e-dagang/</a><br><br>\r\n', 12),
(25, 'What is scareware?', 'https://www.youtube.com/embed/peukxBCPESQ', 1, 'Scareware is a type of social engineering scam that uses fear to trick people into buying useless programs or downloading malware disguised as antivirus software. In the classic example, scareware alerts the victim to a virus on their device, then tries to sell the victim a fake antivirus software that does nothing or turns out to be malware. Scareware uses fear to trick people into buying useless programs or downloading malware disguised as antivirus software.<br><br>\r\nExample: \"Phone Update Recommended\" scam<br><br>\r\nIt targets Android device users. This scheme attempts to trick visitors into downloading/installing and/or purchasing recommended software - by claiming that it will improve the device&#39;s poor performance.<br><br>\r\n\r\n<center><img class=\"img-content\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image71.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center><br><br>\r\n\r\nThe scam states that the user&#39;s phone has a recommended update. The fake pop-up is presented as a notification from Google Play.\r\nThe scheme then claims that the visitor&#39;s device is exhibiting poor processor performance and low memory. However, according to the scam, this can be fixed within seconds by installing a free Android anti-virus and using it to clean the phone.\r\n\r\n', 13),
(26, 'What is the impact on scareware victims?', 'image56.png', 2, 'If a user falls victim to scareware and downloads the fake software, the best-case scenario is that they just wasted money on useless bloatware. Bloatware is unwanted software that is installed on a computer or device. However, this bloatware could make the user susceptible to other attacks if it is not secure. This sort of scareware is just meant to make money off of the initial purchase.\r\nBut often the impact is more malicious. Scareware that installs intentionally malicious software on a victim&#39;s device cloud can do the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n  <li>spy on users</li>\r\n  <li>steal personally identifiable information</li>\r\n  <li>steal credit card or bank account details</li>\r\n  <li>deploy more financial fraud or identity theft software</li>\r\n  <li>lock up the user&#39;s computer and demand a ransom, destroying the files if not paid</li>\r\n  <li>offer fake tech support to con more money out of the victim</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n', 14),
(27, 'How does scareware work?', 'image9.jpg', 2, 'Scareware typically follows a specific pattern. Pop-ups will start appearing, warning users of dangerous files that have been detected on the user&#39;s device. Those pop-ups will try and replicate the logos and layout of legitimate security software. The pop-ups will continue appearing, prompting the user to remove the detected threats or to register for antivirus software.<br><br>\r\nThis is where cybercriminals take advantage of social engineering. The concept of social engineering is about manipulating others into taking actions they would not normally take, such as giving up potentially confidential information. In this case, the social engineering tactics use fear to push users into buying potentially malicious software. This can happen on both desktop and mobile platforms.<br><br>\r\nA link attachment tries to convince the user to pay money for useless bloatware, or to install malware onto their device.<br><br>\r\nOther ways cybercriminals could scam individuals with scareware, aside from using pop-ups, include using malvertising and phishing emails. Scareware then stays on a user&#39;s device for extended periods of time, analyzing their activities.\r\n\r\n', 14),
(28, 'How do you detect scareware?', 'image161.png', 2, 'To minimize the impact of a Scareware attack, which could be very devastating, early detection plays a crucial role. Hence, one must be aware of some viable tactics that are useful for spotting such attacks in action. Here are what works mostly:<br><br>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Fishy Pop-ups\r\n    <p>Your system is under the threat of a Scareware when you’re seeing too many pop-up messages/content on the screen. Any safe and authorized software installed on the system will not send such frequent pop-ups. Also, a pop-up message delivered via malware is certainly a bit different. For instance, it will keep floating, again and again, the text won’t be very clear, and the colors will be a bit faded. From its looks itself, the pop-up message doesn’t seem genuine. One can easily make out that it’s fake.</p>\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Fear-inciting Messages\r\n    <p>If you get constant fear-infesting notifications or messages like your system is under attack, download the anti-virus now to protect your device, your data is leaked, and so on, understand that a hacker is planning a Scareware attack on you. The scarier would be the notification, higher are the possibilities of succeeding in the attack. Legitimate software doesn’t advertise like that.</p>\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Blocked Access to Old files\r\n    <p>When you’re facing trouble accessing your previously saved system files to the browser, then it’s mostly because of malware that is blocking the pathway.</p>\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Fake System Update Suggestions\r\n    <p>Stay alert after constant update requests from software as it&#39;s traps to lure you into a Scareware attack. If you want to check available software update details, go to Setting > App > Updates.</p>\r\n  </li>\r\n  <li>\r\n    Degradation in Performance\r\n    <p>The presence of malware on a system will cause certain obvious operational faults like slow computer performance, excessive battery drainage, frequent unresponsiveness, screen blur, and so on. It’s because of the excessive burden that the device is facing because of the presence of malware.</p>\r\n  </li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<br><center><img class=\"img-content\" src=\"/socialshield/uploads/content/image219.png?txt=128381@_7djajhufa8__\"></center>\r\n', 15),
(29, 'How do you remove scareware?', 'image401.jpg', 2, 'The easiest way to remove scareware is to use a legitimate antivirus program. These programs run scans and detect threats to remove malware. Users can also remove scareware malware manually.<br><br>\r\nThe process to manually remove scareware is normally straightforward. It involves identifying and uninstalling the malicious download. Scareware typically hides in plain sight as a legitimate antivirus program.<br>\r\n<ol>\r\n  <li>Turn off your computers immediately. As long as you&#39;re using your computer, your data and details are under attack.</li>\r\n  <li>If you need to use your system anyhow, try to use it without any internet connection. It’s the internet connectivity that is keeping the malware and the hacker linked. So, destroy that link to minimize the damage.</li>\r\n  <li>Take your infected system to an IT expert. As a novice, you won’t be able to find the severity of the attack. Hence, it’s better to take professional help.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', 15),
(30, 'How can you prevent scareware?', 'image54.jpg', 2, '<ol>\r\n  <li>Use trusted security software. Tools such as an antivirus product can scan devices and detect and remove malware such as scareware.</li>\r\n  <li>Use common sense. Do not click on in-browser pop-ups about security. Do not provide personal or financial information to untrusted or unknown websites.</li>\r\n  <li>Use pop-up blockers, firewalls, and URL filters. These will help prevent pop-ups from showing up and stop attacks.</li>\r\n  <li>Keep browsers updated. This keeps the browser secure, potentially helping to eliminate any weaknesses to scareware pop-ups.</li>\r\n  <li>Close the browser rather than just the pop-up notification. Some scareware techniques scam users by having a fake Close or X button that installs malware when selected. This is known as clickjacking.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', 15);

